<h3>Price Tiers and Quality Expectations</h3>

<p>In the <strong>$15-25 range</strong>, expect crisp, food-friendly Sauvignon Blancs from established regions like New Zealand's Marlborough (Oyster Bay, Whitehaven) or France's Loire Valley appellations. These wines offer classic varietal character with bright acidity and clean mineral finishes, perfect for weeknight dinners.</p>

<p>The <strong>$25-50 tier</strong> delivers exceptional complexity and terroir expression. Look for premium Sancerre from producers like Henri Bourgeois, Marlborough single-vineyard bottlings from Cloudy Bay or Dog Point, and California's Russian River Valley expressions from Merry Edwards. These wines showcase nuanced minerality, extended lees aging, and distinctive regional characteristics.</p>

<p><strong>$50-100 bottles</strong> represent the pinnacle of Sauvignon Blanc craftsmanship. Iconic Sancerre from Domaine Henri Bourgeois "Le Bourgeois" or Pouilly-Fumé from Didier Dagueneau offer decades-long aging potential with profound mineral complexity. Premium Bordeaux Blanc blends and limited-production California bottlings also occupy this tier.</p>

<p>At <strong>$100+</strong>, you're investing in legendary producers like Pascal Jolivet's prestige cuvées or rare library releases from top Marlborough estates with extended bottle age.</p>

